<section xml:id="Section-Unit-Vector-in-the-Direction-of-a-Given-Vector" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Unit Vector in the Direction of a Given Vector</title>

  <p>
    Recall that a <em>unit</em> vector is a vector of length 1.  
    Given a non-zero vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, we can find a unit vector in the same direction by multiplying <m>\mathbf{v}</m> by an appropriate scalar.  
    For example, if <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}a\\b\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\norm{\mathbf{v}}=3</m>, then a unit vector <m>\mathbf{u}</m> in the same direction is given by <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}a/3\\b/3\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}a/\norm{\mathbf{v}}\\b/\norm{\mathbf{v}}\end{bmatrix}</m>.
  </p>

