  <p>
    In general, dividing a non-zero vector by its own magnitude produces a unit vector in the same direction.  We summarize this observation in a theorem.
  </p>


  <theorem xml:id="th-unit">
    <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}v_1\\v_2\\\vdots\\v_n\end{bmatrix}</m> be a non-zero vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. Vector <m>\mathbf{u}</m> given by
          <me>
            \mathbf{u}=\frac{1}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}v_1/\norm{\mathbf{v}}\\v_2/\norm{\mathbf{v}}\\\vdots\\v_n/\norm{\mathbf{v}}\end{bmatrix}
          </me>
          is a unit vector in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Because <m>\mathbf{u}</m> is a positive scalar multiple of <m>\mathbf{v}</m>, <m>\mathbf{u}</m> points in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.  We now show that <m>\norm{\mathbf{u}}=1</m>.
        <md>
          <mrow> \norm{\mathbf{u}}\amp=\amp\sqrt{ \Big(\frac{v_1}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}\Big)^2+\Big(\frac{v_2}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}\Big)^2+\ldots +\Big(\frac{v_n}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}\Big)^2} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\amp\frac{1}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}\sqrt{v_1^2+v_2^2+\ldots +v_n^2} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp=\amp\frac{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}{\norm{\mathbf{v}}}=1 </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </proof>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="reference">
  <p>
    Find a unit vector in the direction of <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\\1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    We first compute <m>\norm{\mathbf{v}}</m>.
    <me>
        \norm{\mathbf{v}}=\sqrt{4+9+1+1}=\sqrt{15}
    </me>
    By <xref ref="th-unit"/>, 
    <me>
        \mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix}2/\sqrt{15}\\-3/\sqrt{15}\\1/\sqrt{15}\\0\\1/\sqrt{15}\end{bmatrix}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{15}}\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\\1\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}
    </me>
  </p>
</example>

<subsection xml:id="Subsection-Practice-Problems">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>
  <exercises>
    <exercisegroup>
    
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find a unit vector in the direction of the given vector <m>\mathbf{v}</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
    
      <exercise xml:id="prob-00361">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}-3\\4\end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix} -0.6\\ 0.8 \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise xml:id="prob-00362">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}2\\-3\\6\end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix} 2/7\\ -3/7\\ 6/7 \end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise xml:id="prob-00363">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}1\\3\\-2\end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>        
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>\mathbf{u}=\begin{bmatrix} 1/\sqrt{14}\\ 3/\sqrt{14}\\ -2/\sqrt{14}\end{bmatrix}</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercise xml:id="prob-00364">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\mathbf{v}=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\\sqrt{7}\end{bmatrix}</m>.
          Apply the concepts from this section to find a vector <m>\mathbf{w}</m> that points in the same direction as <m>\mathbf{v}</m> and whose length is 5.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\mathbf{w}=\begin{bmatrix} -5/3\\ 5/3\\ 5\sqrt{7}/3 \end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
</subsection>
</section>